1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:05,240
They say price action never 
lies! And this it’s 100% true! 

2
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:11,240
So get ready to take some notes, because today 
you’ll discover several strategies that reveal  

3
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:17,320
exactly when big money enters the market.
Nothing complicated, just simple price action  

4
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:21,480
combined with some basic volume analysis!
 
Engulfing gap 

5
00:00:21,480 --> 00:00:27,280
Let’s start with the engulfing gap concept!
Engulfing gaps are a big sign in the market. 

6
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:31,880
They show up when prices jump 
a lot from one day to the next. 

7
00:00:31,880 --> 00:00:35,800
And they can tell us a lot 
about what might happen next.
  

8
00:00:35,800 --> 00:00:42,960
A bullish engulfing gap is when the price opens 
lower than the last close, but then shoots up and  

9
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:47,880
closes higher than the last open.
This means buyers came in  

10
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:51,800
strong. They pushed the price up a lot.
 
A bearish engulfing gap is the opposite.  

11
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:58,640
The price opens higher than the last close, but 
then falls and closes lower than the last open. 

12
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:02,840
This shows sellers took control. 
They pushed the price down hard. 

13
00:01:02,840 --> 00:01:06,680
These gaps can show the start 
of a new momentum move.
  

14
00:01:06,680 --> 00:01:12,240
And of course, not all gaps are the same.
Some gaps are more important than others. 

15
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:17,520
If a market has been going up for a 
while and then has a big bullish gap,  

16
00:01:17,520 --> 00:01:22,720
that might be a sign of strength. It 
could mean the uptrend is still strong.
  

17
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:28,160
But if a market has been going up for 
a long time and then has a bearish gap,  

18
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:32,960
that could be a warning sign. It 
might mean the uptrend is ending.
  

19
00:01:32,960 --> 00:01:38,040
The same for downtrends. A bearish gap 
in a downtrend might mean the trend is  

20
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:44,400
still strong. But a bullish gap could 
be a sign the downtrend is ending.
  

21
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:50,880
Now, you don't just jump in as soon as you see 
a gap. First big thing to look at is volume. 

22
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:56,960
High volume with a gap is a strong signal. 
It means lots of people are trading. They  

23
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:04,200
all agree on which way the price should go. Low 
volume might mean the gap isn't as important.
  

24
00:02:04,200 --> 00:02:09,720
Another thing to look at is the overall 
trend. Is the market in an uptrend or a  

25
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:17,120
downtrend? Engulfing gaps that go with the trend 
are often stronger than gaps against the trend .
 
  

26
00:02:17,120 --> 00:02:24,320
There are 3 different types of engulfing gaps: 
Breakaway gaps, Runaway gaps and Exhaustion gaps. 

27
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:28,400
Breakaway gaps happen at the start 
of a new trend. They're like the  

28
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:33,520
market breaking out of an old pattern.
Runaway gaps happen during a strong  

29
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:40,680
trend. They mean the trend picking up speed.
And exhaustion gaps happen at the end of a trend.  

30
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:47,000
They're the last push before the trend ends .
 
Engulfing gaps can be any of these types.  

31
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,360
The type matters because it can 
tell you what might happen next. 

32
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:57,160
For instance, if you see a bullish engulfing 
gap that looks like a breakaway gap,  

33
00:02:57,160 --> 00:03:02,760
it might be the start of a new uptrend. 
That could be a good time to buy.
  

34
00:03:02,760 --> 00:03:09,160
But if you see a bullish engulfing gap that looks 
like an exhaustion gap, it might be the end of an  

35
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:16,000
uptrend. That could be a good time to sell.
 
Gaps can be tricky. Sometimes they fill  

36
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:22,480
quickly. This means the price moves back to 
where it was before the gap. Other times,  

37
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:27,960
this gap fill might take a longer time.
That why if you buy after a bullish engulfing  

38
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:34,440
gap, you need put your stop below the low of the 
gap. If the price falls below that, it might mean  

39
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:41,280
the gap wasn't as strong as you thought.
 
Also, engulfing gaps can create support and  

40
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:48,920
resistance levels. This means prices might have 
trouble moving through the gap area in the future. 

41
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:55,640
For example, if a market gaps up, that gap 
area might become support. If the price  

42
00:03:55,640 --> 00:04:02,360
falls back to that area later, it might 
stop falling and start going up again. 

43
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:06,880
This can be useful for finding 
other entry and exit points. 

44
00:04:06,880 --> 00:04:13,000
You might buy when the price bounces off a gap 
support. Or you might sell when the price hits  

45
00:04:13,000 --> 00:05:35,760
a gap resistance.
 
 
 
 
Momentum recharge

46
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:42,840
The next concept is called the momentum recharge.
After a big momentum day, the market often takes  

47
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:48,480
a breather. And during this contraction 
phase, you’ll see liquidity sweeps,  

48
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:55,240
trapping the traders expecting a reversal.
So when the market moves a lot in one day,  

49
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:59,640
most of the times, it pauses to 
rest the next day, or even days,  

50
00:06:00,240 --> 00:06:05,080
and figure out what to do next.
 
First, some traders want to cash  

51
00:06:05,080 --> 00:06:10,800
in on their wins. They sell some of their 
positions to lock in their profits. This  

52
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:17,760
selling can slow down the market's movement.
Also, traders need time to think. Big market  

53
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:24,960
moves often happen because of news or volatility 
increase. After the first rush of excitement,  

54
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:29,640
people want to sit back and really 
think about what the news means. 

55
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:35,400
Also, after a big move, there might not be 
many traders left who want to keep pushing  

56
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:39,760
the market in the same direction.
That’s why, you might see the  

57
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:46,080
price moving sideways in a range. 
 
The volume often drops during this time too. 

58
00:06:46,080 --> 00:06:50,360
The market is getting ready 
for its next big move.
  

59
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:57,200
Here's how to pinpoint the contraction: You simply 
look at the "isolated pivot highs and lows". 

60
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:01,120
These are like the edges of the 
box the price is moving in. 
 
  

61
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:06,400
When the market breaks out of 
contraction, it often starts a new trend. 

62
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:11,800
And this breakout can happen in either 
direction - up or down. But I only  

63
00:07:11,800 --> 00:07:18,120
trade in the direction of the previous move.
If the previous move was a strong upward one,  

64
00:07:18,120 --> 00:07:25,040
I mainly look to buy, after the contraction phase.
You want to see the price clearly break out  

65
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:29,280
of its contraction range .
 
One way to confirm a breakout  

66
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:33,200
is to look at the volume.
If the volume increases as  

67
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:39,480
the price breaks out, that's a good sign.
You look for those isolated pivot points to  

68
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:45,640
spot the range. And you wait patiently for 
a clear breakout with increasing volume,  

69
00:07:45,640 --> 00:07:51,000
before making your next move.
 
One interesting thing about contraction  

70
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:56,400
is that it often happens at certain 
times of the day in the Forex market. 

71
00:07:56,400 --> 00:08:01,400
So let’s say the market went up quite 
a lot during a whole trading day. 

72
00:08:01,400 --> 00:08:07,960
The next day, there's often a consolidation period 
during the Asian trading session. This contraction  

73
00:08:07,960 --> 00:08:13,760
can also last during the London session.
 
Other times, when London opens,  

74
00:08:13,760 --> 00:08:19,080
there's often a breakout.
New York's opening can cause another shake-up. 

75
00:08:20,960 --> 00:08:24,920
These patterns can help you 
time your trades better.
  

76
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:28,800
During this contraction phase, 
expect some liquidity sweeps,  

77
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:34,000
to bait and trap reversal traders.
If the price drops below the bottom  

78
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:39,640
of the contraction, it might be a sign 
that big players are actually buying. 

79
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:46,800
They push the price down to trigger stop losses 
and scare some traders out of their positions. 

80
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:53,040
Then, they buy at the lower prices. If the price 
then moves back above the contraction and stays  

81
00:08:53,040 --> 00:08:59,440
there, it could be the start of an upward move.
 
 
The opposite is true for downward moves.  

82
00:09:00,080 --> 00:09:06,280
If the price spikes above the range and 
then falls back below it and stays there,  

83
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:09,760
it could be the start of a downward move. 

84
00:09:09,760 --> 00:09:13,560
During this contraction, 
something interesting happens. 

85
00:09:13,560 --> 00:09:18,640
The price will often make quick moves in 
the opposite direction of the big move. 

86
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:23,480
If the big move was up, you might 
see the price dip down briefly. 

87
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:27,840
If the big move was down, 
you might see small jumps up. 

88
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:31,640
These quick moves are the 
liquidity sweeps we talked about.
 
  

89
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:37,080
It's all about tricking traders and 
finding money to fuel the next big move. 

90
00:09:37,080 --> 00:09:43,080
You see, after a big move up, some traders 
think the price will come back down. They  

91
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:49,960
place orders to sell when the price drops a bit.
And the market knows this. So it drops the price  

92
00:09:49,960 --> 00:09:56,160
just enough to trigger these sell orders.
But then, instead of keeping going down,  

93
00:09:56,160 --> 00:10:01,000
it often bounces right back up .
This is called inducement. It's  

94
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:06,680
meant to catch traders who are trying to 
guess when the price will turn around. 
 
  

95
00:10:06,680 --> 00:10:11,880
These reversal traders are looking for 
the point where an up-move turns into a  

96
00:10:11,880 --> 00:10:16,800
down-move, or the other way around.
If you understand these sweeps,  

97
00:10:16,800 --> 00:10:22,920
you can avoid falling into the trap.
Instead of selling when you see that small drop,  

98
00:10:22,920 --> 00:10:28,840
you might wait to see if it's just a sweep.
And you might even use it as a chance to buy,  

99
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:32,440
with the big players.
 
So, next time you see a big  

100
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:39,720
momentum day in the market, don't get too excited.
Instead, start looking for signs of contraction.  

101
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:44,320
Watch for those isolated pivot points.
Keep an eye on the volume. 

102
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:59,240
Be patient, and wait for a clear 
breakout or a liquidity sweep. 
 
  

103
00:11:09,320 --> 00:12:00,240
Pattern Pitfall Syndrome 

104
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:14,840
I like to call the next concept 
the Pattern Pitfall Syndrome. 

105
00:12:14,840 --> 00:12:18,880
When we start trading, we are 
immediately bombarded with chart  

106
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:25,920
patterns. Triangles, wedges, pennants.
But trading these patterns can be tricky. 

107
00:12:25,920 --> 00:12:30,320
Many traders get caught in traps when 
they try to trade these patterns,  

108
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:36,480
because these are actually tough to trade.
 
Basically, triangles and wedges are patterns where  

109
00:12:36,480 --> 00:12:42,120
the price moves in a smaller and smaller range.
It's like the market is taking a deep breath  

110
00:12:42,120 --> 00:12:45,760
before making a big move.
The problem is, it's hard  

111
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:50,800
to know which way that move will go.
Now, many trading books tell you to wait for  

112
00:12:50,800 --> 00:12:56,800
the price to break out of the triangle or wedge.
Then you're supposed to jump in and ride the new  

113
00:12:56,800 --> 00:13:02,800
trend. Sounds easy… but it's not that simple!
 
One big problem is what traders call  

114
00:13:02,800 --> 00:13:06,040
"liquidity clear-outs".
This is when the price looks  

115
00:13:06,040 --> 00:13:12,120
like it's breaking out, but then it quickly 
turns around and goes back into the pattern. 

116
00:13:12,120 --> 00:13:16,440
This happens because the market 
is always looking for liquidity. 

117
00:13:16,440 --> 00:13:21,400
That's just a fancy way of saying it's 
looking for people to trade with. 
  

118
00:13:21,400 --> 00:13:28,200
When price is in a tight range, like in a triangle 
or wedge, there's not much trading going on. 

119
00:13:28,200 --> 00:13:33,800
So, the market might push the price out 
of the pattern just to get some action. 

120
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:38,400
And big players use these 
patterns to trap other traders. 

121
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:44,240
They push the price out of the pattern on 
purpose. This makes some traders react. 

122
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:47,760
And then the price is pushed 
back into the pattern. Now  

123
00:13:47,760 --> 00:13:54,120
those traders are stuck in a bad trade.
 
This is why blindly following breakouts from  

124
00:13:54,120 --> 00:14:00,360
these patterns can lead to a lot of losing trades.
I admit I’ve lost a lot of trades chasing  

125
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:04,760
breakouts from triangles.
So, what can you do? Well,  

126
00:14:04,760 --> 00:14:11,080
if you're in your first year, it might be best to 
avoid these patterns for now. They look simple,  

127
00:14:11,080 --> 00:14:17,960
but they're actually pretty complex. In hindsight, 
on the left side of the chart, they look obvious. 

128
00:14:17,960 --> 00:14:21,360
But it takes a lot of experience 
to tell the difference between  

129
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:26,760
a real breakout and a fake-out .
 
If you do want to trade these patterns,  

130
00:14:26,760 --> 00:14:32,040
here are some things to think about:
First, don't rush in. Just because  

131
00:14:32,040 --> 00:14:36,920
the price moves out of the pattern 
doesn't mean it's a real breakout. 

132
00:14:36,920 --> 00:14:43,320
Look at the bigger picture. What's happening in 
the larger trend? Is this breakout going with  

133
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:50,760
or against that trend? Breakouts that go with 
the larger trend are more likely to be real. 

134
00:14:50,760 --> 00:14:56,920
Pay attention to volume. A real breakout 
often comes with an increase in volume.  

135
00:14:56,920 --> 00:15:03,560
If the price is breaking out but volume is 
low, be careful. It might be a fake-out. 

136
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:08,200
Consider the time of day. In 
the Forex market, for example,  

137
00:15:08,200 --> 00:15:14,040
breakouts often happen when a new trading 
session opens. The Asian session is often  

138
00:15:14,040 --> 00:15:19,480
quiet, but when London opens, 
there's often more action.
 
  

139
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:21,480
The Exhaustion Wick Illusion
The next concept is the Exhaustion  

140
00:15:21,480 --> 00:15:28,160
Wick Illusion, and involves candles 
with long wicks, pin bars basically. 

141
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:32,600
Pin bars are a popular trading 
pattern, but they can be tricky. 

142
00:15:32,600 --> 00:15:38,440
When they show up after big price moves, 
they might not be as reliable as you think. 

143
00:15:38,440 --> 00:15:44,360
The long wick shows that the price tried 
to go one way but then changed its mind. 

144
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:49,040
Traders often see this as a sign 
that the price might turn around .
  

145
00:15:49,040 --> 00:15:53,800
But here's the thing. When a pin bar 
shows up after a big momentum move,  

146
00:15:53,800 --> 00:15:59,040
it might not mean what you think it means.
That’s because big price moves can  

147
00:15:59,040 --> 00:16:04,840
mess with how the market usually works.
 
Let's say the price has been falling a lot.  

148
00:16:04,840 --> 00:16:11,320
Then you see a pin bar with a long lower wick.
You might think the price is going to go up now. 

149
00:16:11,320 --> 00:16:15,920
But that's not always the case.
The market might still be feeling the effects of  

150
00:16:15,920 --> 00:16:22,520
whatever made the price fall in the first place.
 
Or think about it this way. After a big move,  

151
00:16:22,520 --> 00:16:27,680
some traders might be taking their profits.
If the price went up a lot,  

152
00:16:27,680 --> 00:16:32,480
some traders who bought low might 
be selling to lock in their gains. 

153
00:16:32,480 --> 00:16:39,040
This selling can create a pin bar, but it doesn't 
mean the price is going to start falling.
  

154
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:43,800
Here's another reason to be careful. 
Big players in the market might use  

155
00:16:43,800 --> 00:16:49,040
these situations to trick other traders.
They might push the price just enough  

156
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:54,440
to create a pin bar, making some 
traders think a reversal is coming. 

157
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:59,320
But then the price keeps going 
in the same direction as before.
  

158
00:16:59,320 --> 00:17:04,480
So, what can you do? Well, one thing 
is to look at the bigger picture. 

159
00:17:04,480 --> 00:17:09,600
Pay attention to where the pin bar 
forms. Is it at an important level? 

160
00:17:09,600 --> 00:17:15,160
Maybe a support or resistance level. 
Or at a fresh, unmitigated supply or  

161
00:17:15,160 --> 00:17:23,080
demand area that's been important in the past?
If so, the pin bar might be more meaningful.
  

162
00:17:23,080 --> 00:17:28,960
Another thing to watch is what happens after 
the pin bar. Does the price quickly move in the  

163
00:17:28,960 --> 00:17:33,080
direction the pin bar suggests?
Or does it just sit there,  

164
00:17:33,080 --> 00:17:39,680
not doing much? A real reversal signal 
should lead to some follow-through.
  

165
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:45,840
Volume can be a helpful clue too. If you 
see a pin bar with a lot more trading volume  

166
00:17:45,840 --> 00:17:53,160
than usual, it might be more significant.
High volume means more traders are involved,  

167
00:17:53,160 --> 00:17:58,840
which could mean a real change in the market .
 
Here's something else to think about.  

168
00:17:59,560 --> 00:18:05,160
Sometimes, what looks like a reversal 
is just the market taking a breather. 

169
00:18:05,160 --> 00:18:09,760
Remember the previous concept we 
talked before. After a big move,  

170
00:18:09,760 --> 00:18:16,480
the price often pauses or pulls back a bit 
before continuing in the same direction. 

171
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:21,920
This is normal and doesn't always 
mean a full reversal is coming .
  

172
00:18:21,920 --> 00:18:27,800
Again, think about the time of day.
For example, pin bars that form at the start  

173
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:33,720
of a new trading session might be more meaningful.
There's often more activity when a new session  

174
00:18:33,720 --> 00:18:40,800
opens, which can lead to real reversals.
Think about it. When a new trading session starts,  

175
00:18:40,800 --> 00:18:45,240
a lot of things happen. Traders 
are coming back to their desks. 

176
00:18:45,240 --> 00:18:51,360
They're looking at what happened while they 
were away. They're making new plans for the day. 

177
00:18:51,360 --> 00:18:58,000
All this can lead to more buying and selling.
 
Now, let's say you see a pin bar right when the  

178
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:04,800
London session opens. This could be a big 
deal, because London is a major Forex hub. 

179
00:19:04,800 --> 00:19:12,040
When it opens, there's often a burst of activity. 
Prices might move a lot. And if a pin bar forms  

180
00:19:12,040 --> 00:19:21,480
during this time, it might show a valid shift 
in the market, at least for a short period.
  

181
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:27,000
The same thing can happen when New York opens. 
These are times when big players enter the  

182
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:34,800
market. Their trades can really move the market .
Sometimes, different sessions overlap. There's a  

183
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:41,240
time when both London and New York are open.
This is often a very active time. If you see  

184
00:19:41,240 --> 00:19:49,200
a pin bar during this overlap, at a key level, 
it might be worth paying extra attention to.
  

185
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:55,080
And it's not just about the start of sessions. 
The end of sessions can be important too. 

186
00:19:55,080 --> 00:20:01,200
As a session closes, some traders might be 
closing out their positions. This can lead  

187
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:07,200
to price moves and maybe even pin bars.
 
You need to do some backtesting here. 

188
00:20:07,200 --> 00:20:12,200
Look at the start and end times of 
major sessions on your charts. And  

189
00:20:12,200 --> 00:20:18,000
try to see if you spot pin bar patterns.
Maybe you notice that pin bars at certain  

190
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:22,400
times tend to be more reliable.
Or maybe you see that certain  

191
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:28,680
times of day often lead to fake-outs.
This kind of backtest can be really valuable  

192
00:20:28,680 --> 00:21:52,280
and save you many losing trades.
 
 
 
Buying/selling climaxes

193
00:21:52,280 --> 00:21:57,280
One of the most important concepts 
is buying or selling climax. 

194
00:21:57,280 --> 00:22:04,880
Trading is a battle between participants. On one 
side, you have buyers, and on the other, sellers. 

195
00:22:04,880 --> 00:22:11,560
Most of the time, they're pretty evenly matched.
But sometimes, one side gets really strong.  

196
00:22:11,560 --> 00:22:16,160
That's when we see climaxes.
 
Let's start with the buying climax. 

197
00:22:16,160 --> 00:22:21,520
These happen when buyers get excited. 
Maybe there's good news. Maybe the price  

198
00:22:21,520 --> 00:22:27,520
has been going up for a while. Whatever the 
reason, suddenly everyone wants to buy.
  

199
00:22:27,520 --> 00:22:32,800
So picture this: The price is going up. 
It's been going up for a while. Then,  

200
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:38,720
out of nowhere, it starts going up even faster.
The volume gets really high. This is key. High  

201
00:22:38,720 --> 00:22:44,280
volume means lots of people are buying.
And here's the tricky part. While all these  

202
00:22:44,280 --> 00:22:50,720
people are buying, the smart traders are selling.
They know something the buyers don't. They  

203
00:22:50,720 --> 00:22:55,120
know that when everyone's buying, 
it's often a good time to sell. 

204
00:22:55,120 --> 00:22:58,640
That’s because after a buying 
climax, there's often a drop  

205
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:06,520
in price. The market has run out of buyers. 
Everyone who wanted to buy has already bought. 
  

206
00:23:06,520 --> 00:23:11,200
Now, let's flip it for a selling climax.
The price has been going down.  

207
00:23:11,200 --> 00:23:17,560
Then it starts going down even faster.
The volume gets really high. Everyone's selling. 

208
00:23:17,560 --> 00:23:22,920
But just like with buying climaxes, 
the big traders are doing the opposite. 

209
00:23:22,920 --> 00:23:27,280
They're buying when everyone else 
is selling. They know that after a  

210
00:23:27,280 --> 00:23:34,160
big sell-off, prices often go back up.
 
 
So how can you spot these climaxes? You  

211
00:23:34,160 --> 00:23:37,960
look for several signs!
For a buying climax: 

212
00:23:37,960 --> 00:23:42,200
The price is going up fast.
The volume is super high. 

213
00:23:42,200 --> 00:23:47,080
The price bars are getting narrow, 
they are decreasing in size.
  

214
00:23:47,080 --> 00:23:51,080
And for a selling climax:
The price is dropping fast. 

215
00:23:51,080 --> 00:23:56,600
Again, the volume is super high.
And the price bars are narrow .
  

216
00:23:56,600 --> 00:24:02,760
Now, why are these climaxes important? 
Because they often mark the end of a trend. 

217
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:08,640
After a buying climax, the price might 
start going down. After a selling climax,  

218
00:24:08,640 --> 00:24:12,760
it might start going up.
But be careful. Just because  

219
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:19,080
you see a climax doesn't mean the trend 
will change right away, on the next candle! 

220
00:24:19,080 --> 00:24:25,200
Sometimes the market can stay irrational for a 
while. That's why you wait for confirmation . 

221
00:24:25,200 --> 00:24:31,160
You want to see the price actually start to 
move in the new direction. Don't just assume the  

222
00:24:31,160 --> 00:24:38,640
trend will change because you saw a climax. 
 
Let's analyze a bit deeper a buying climax. 

223
00:24:38,640 --> 00:24:45,360
Remember, these happen at the end of an uptrend.
The price has been going up for a while. Then it  

224
00:24:45,360 --> 00:24:50,200
makes one last big push higher.
During this last push,  

225
00:24:50,200 --> 00:24:55,000
you'll see some telltale signs.
The volume will be really high.  

226
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:01,520
In this case, lots of people are buying.
You will also start to see "narrow spreads".  

227
00:25:01,520 --> 00:25:07,720
This means the difference between the high and 
low price for each bar (or candle) is small. 

228
00:25:07,720 --> 00:25:11,880
This can happen when there's a 
lot of excitement in the market. 

229
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:18,120
Another thing to watch for: the market 
might close in the middle or low of the bar. 

230
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:22,680
This means that even though there was 
a lot of buying, the price couldn't  

231
00:25:22,680 --> 00:25:26,200
hold onto all its gains.
This can be a sign that  

232
00:25:26,200 --> 00:25:33,000
the buying pressure is starting to weaken .
 
The same for selling climaxes. These happen at  

233
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:40,360
the end of a downtrend. The price has been falling 
for a while. Then it makes one last big drop. 

234
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:45,680
Just like with buying climaxes, 
you'll see high volume. But this time,  

235
00:25:45,680 --> 00:25:51,840
it's because lots of people are selling. 
You might also see narrow spreads here too. 

236
00:25:51,840 --> 00:25:58,400
So there’s a lot of effort, the volume, but 
the result, the candle, is narrow. When you  

237
00:25:58,400 --> 00:26:04,360
have a high volume, you want to see a 
large candle. But that’s not the case here. 

238
00:26:04,360 --> 00:26:10,240
In a selling climax, the market might 
close in the middle or high of the bar. 

239
00:26:10,240 --> 00:26:15,600
This shows that even though there was a lot 
of selling, the price couldn't keep falling. 

240
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:22,840
A sign that selling pressure might be easing up.
 
Climaxes can happen in any market and any  

241
00:26:22,840 --> 00:26:29,680
timeframe. You might see one on a 5-minute 
chart or you might spot one on a daily chart. 

242
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:36,040
The principles are the same, but the effects 
might last for different lengths of time.
  

243
00:26:36,040 --> 00:26:41,600
Now, what happens after a climax?
After a buying climax, big traders  

244
00:26:41,600 --> 00:26:48,840
start looking for signs of weakness. They know 
that the market has probably run out of buyers. 

245
00:26:48,840 --> 00:26:55,200
What might this weakness look like? Maybe 
the price tries to go higher but fails. 

246
00:26:55,200 --> 00:27:02,440
Or maybe it starts making lower highs.
These are signs that the uptrend might be over.
  

247
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:08,720
After a selling climax, it's the opposite. 
The big boys look for signs of strength.  

248
00:27:08,720 --> 00:27:14,960
Maybe the price bounces off a low. Or maybe 
it starts making higher lows. These could  

249
00:27:14,960 --> 00:27:21,680
be signs that the downtrend is ending.
 
Just because you see a possible climax  

250
00:27:21,680 --> 00:27:26,600
doesn't mean you should immediately 
open a trade in the opposite direction. 

251
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:31,800
Try to find some sort of confirmation.
It could be something simple,  

252
00:27:31,800 --> 00:27:37,720
like a break of a trendline.
Or a move above or below a key level. Maybe you  

253
00:27:37,720 --> 00:27:43,680
find a change of character on a lower time frame.
The specific confirmation you look for  

254
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:48,400
might depend on your trading style.
But the important thing is to have some kind  

255
00:27:48,400 --> 00:27:54,840
of proof that the trend is actually changing.
 
 
Here's another point: climaxes often happen  

256
00:27:54,840 --> 00:27:57,720
when there's big news.
For a buying climax,  

257
00:27:57,720 --> 00:28:03,360
the news might be really good. For a 
selling climax, it might be really bad. 

258
00:28:03,360 --> 00:28:08,760
But smart money know that news alone 
doesn't determine where the market goes. 

259
00:28:08,760 --> 00:28:15,000
They look at how the market reacts to the news.
 
Again, the timeframe of the climax matters. 

260
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:21,720
A climax on a 5-minute chart might lead to 
a reversal that may last for several hours. 

261
00:28:21,720 --> 00:28:27,640
A climax on a daily chart could signal 
a reversal that lasts for weeks. 

262
00:28:27,640 --> 00:28:58,040
The bigger the timeframe, the more 
significant the potential reversal. 

263
00:29:52,720 --> 00:29:56,600
Now, if you’re ready for more smart 
money and price action methods,  

264
00:29:56,600 --> 00:30:06,480
go ahead and watch one of these videos!

